I had a similar(ish) situation, and I was able to make something work using reflection. 

I had a class A, which was loaded using a custom classloader (beyond my control). It wanted to interact with another class, B, which was only loaded using the system classloader, `AppClassLoader`. To &#39;see&#39; them, A had to explicitly use that classloader and create an instance via reflection. 

```
    ClassLoader cl = ClassLoader.getSystemClassLoader();

        // Switch classloaders to the system classloader, rather than the transformer classloader we were loaded with
        try {
            Class&lt;?&gt; clazz = cl.loadClass(&quot;com.example.B&quot;);
            Object b = clazz.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();
        } catch (ClassNotFoundException | InstantiationException | InvocationTargetException | IllegalAccessException | NoSuchMethodException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
```

Things got even messier when I wanted to have B invoke something on A. B had no way at all of getting A&#39;s classloader. I inverted the control, and just passed A&#39;s data, D, to B so that B could do the work. D&#39;s class was also loaded with the A classloader. A had to use reflection to invoke the method on B, and the method signature had to only have JVM core libraries in it, or A could not find the method by reflection. 

```
someMethod(D data[loaded by A-classloader]) != someMethod(D data[loaded by B-classloader])
```

so the method had to be 

```
someMethod(Object data)
```

and B could not cast `data` to `D` because the classloaders were different. It also could not use reflection to invoke methods on `data` if the signature involved &#39;interesting&#39; classes that are loaded by one of the application classloaders. 

I created a D-wrapper, W. W had a method signature simple enough to be found by reflection even from a different classloader, `doSomething(String s)`. B could invoke `doSomething` on W, and W could then invoke the methods with non-JVM-library types. This is ugly, but it works.

Alternatively, if a wrapper can&#39;t do complex enough operations, serialization would also allow passing actual object instances back and forth between classloaders. It&#39;s not great, but it might be cleaner and less hacky than all of the reflection.

