But it makes all other elements invisible also.&lt;br&gt;
**Please if you have any better solution, put it here.**

This has to do with the _recycling_ behavior of the `RecyclerView`. When you scroll a view off of one edge of the screen, the system will eventually re-use that view for another position in your list of words. Since you only conditionally set the visibility of some views, whatever was last set will remain in the re-used view. So, if you click to show the meaning on one word, the next time that view is re-used you will be able to see the meaning of the new word.

With `RecyclerView`, it&#39;s a good idea to always have your data model (your `words` list) be able to fully represent your state. I don&#39;t know exactly what each element in `words` looks like, but I can see that each one has a `getWord()` and a `getMeaning()` function. I think you should add an `isMeaningVisible(): Boolean` function to this as well. Then you can have something like this:

    @Override
    public void onBindViewHolder(@NonNull ViewHolder holder, int position) {
        Word word = words.get(position);
        holder.tv_wordText.setText(word.getWord());
        holder.tv_meaningText.setText(word.getMeaning());
        holder.tv_meaningText_cv.setVisibility(word.isMeaningVisible() ? View.VISIBLE : View.INVISIBLE);
    }

The other question is what to do about the click on the button. I notice that in your code you have `final int pos`; this is not a good idea. `RecyclerView` allows you to insert or remove individual elements, and so the position passed to `onBindViewHolder()` can change over time. Because of this, it&#39;s best to set up click listeners inside `onCreateViewHolder()` instead.

    @NonNull
    @Override
    public ViewHolder onCreateViewHolder(@NonNull ViewGroup parent, int viewType) {
        ViewHolder holder = new ViewHolder(LayoutInflater.from(context).inflate(R.layout.word_list_adapter, parent, false));

        holder.btn_showAnswer.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
            @Override
            public void onClick(View view) {
                int position = holder.getAdapterPosition();
                if (position != RecyclerView.NO_POSITION) {
                    Word word = words.get(position);
                    word.setMeaningVisible(!word.isMeaningVisible());
                    notifyItemChanged(position);
                }
            }
        });

        return holder;
    }

